<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-770-513  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 770 513.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Oct 1990 v23 n10 p73(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>User interface management systems and application portability.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Seacord, Robert C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are software portability problems with the user interfaceand standards activities are beginning to address this issue ofapplication portability across multiple platforms.andP;  One approachis to separate the application from the user interface, making itpractical to change the user interface of the system and possibleto change the user interface toolkits without modifying theapplication software.andP;  The user interface management system (UIMS)encourages separating a software system into an applicationportion and a user interface portion.andP;  Most UIMSs are based on theSeeheim architecture and have three different layers: application,dialogue, and presentation.andP;  Some approaches are: event driven,declarative, object-oriented, data-driven, and interactive layoutsystems.andP;  The IEEE P1201 working group set up an UIMS study groupin Aug 1989 which has evaluated several UIMSs.andP;  The group'sconsensus is that the state of the practice is advanced enough towarrant a standards effort.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardizationInstitute of Electrical and Electronics EngineersUser Interface Management SystemsApplicationsSoftware MigrationSoftware Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   User interface management system architecture. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>